"Simas T., Nunes J.P., Ferreira J.G.","Effects of global climate change on coastal salt marshes",2001,"Ecological Modelling","139","1",,"1","15",,,10.1016/S0304-3800(01)00226-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035970344&partnerID=40&md5=312aa282e88e412113fee7b06cdde4e3","IMAR - Ctr. for Ecological Modelling, Departmento Cie. Engenharia do A., Monte de Caparica, Portugal","Simas, T., IMAR - Ctr. for Ecological Modelling, Departmento Cie. Engenharia do A., Monte de Caparica, Portugal; Nunes, J.P., IMAR - Ctr. for Ecological Modelling, Departmento Cie. Engenharia do A., Monte de Caparica, Portugal; Ferreira, J.G., IMAR - Ctr. for Ecological Modelling, Departmento Cie. Engenharia do A., Monte de Caparica, Portugal","A methodology combining ecological modelling with geographical information analysis and remote sensing was employed to determine the effects of sea-level rise in estuarine salt marshes, using the Tagus estuary (Portugal) as a case study. The development of salt marsh vegetation was simulated separately for C3 and C4 plants, using a combined biogeochemical and demographic model. This simulation, which provided small-scale (m2) results of annual above-ground primary production, was upscaled to the whole salt marsh area, using bathymetry data, remote sensing and Geographic Information System (GIS) for assessing vegetation cover and determining areal distribution of C3 and C4 vegetation. Based on IPCC data, several sea-level rise scenarios were considered, and the coupled ecological model-GIS were applied to these in order to determine changes in global salt marsh productivity. The results indicate that the salt marshes of the mesotidal estuaries such as the Tagus are susceptible to sea-level rise only in a worst case scenario, which is more likely to occur if the terms set out by the Kyoto protocol are not met by several industrialised nations. The low vulnerability of salt marshes supports the suggestion that areas with high tidal ranges are less vulnerable to sea level change, due to greater sediment transport and accretion, Nevertheless, the precautionary principle should always be applied by coastal planners, due to the great uncertainty surrounding forecasts of sea-level rise. © 2001 Elsevier Science B.V.","Benthic primary production; Ecological modelling; GIS; Global warming; Remote sensing; Salt marsh; Sea-level rise; Tagus estuary","climate change; ecological modeling; estuarine ecosystem; GIS; remote sensing; saltmarsh; sea level change; Portugal",,,,,,"Allen, J.R.L., The formation of coastal peat marshes under an upward tendency of relative sea-level (1990) J. Geol. Soc., 147, pp. 743-745; Allen, J.R.L., Salt-marsh growth and stratification: A numerical model with special reference to the Severn Estuary, southwest Britain (1990) Mar. Geol., 95, pp. 77-96; Allen, J.R.L., A continuity-based sedimentological model for temperate-zone tidal salt marshes (1994) J. Geol. Soc., 151, pp. 41-49; Allen, J.R.L., Salt-marsh growth and fluctuating sea-level: Implications of a simulation model for Flandrian coastal stratigraphy and peat-based sea-level curves (1995) Sed. Geol., 100, pp. 21-45; Allen, J.R.L., Simulation models of salt-marsh morphodynamics: Some implications for high-intertidal sediment couplets related to sea-level change (1997) Sed. Geol., 113, pp. 211-223; Bach, H.K., A dynamic model describing the seasonal variations in growth and the distribution of ellgrass (Zostera marina L.). I. Model theory (1993) Ecol. Model., 65, pp. 31-50; Baretta-Bekker, J.G., Baretta, J.W., Ebenhoh, W., Microbial dynamics in the marine ecosystem model ERSEM II with decoupled carbon assimilation and nutrient uptake (1997) J Sea Res., 38, pp. 195-211; Berner, E.K., Berner, R.A., (1996) Global Environment: Water, Air and Geochemical Cycles, , USA: Prentice-Hall; Boumans, R.M.J., Day J.W., Jr., High precision measurements of sediment elevation in shallow coastal areas using a sedimentation-erosion table (1993) Estua